From AIDS, non-communicable diseases in eight fundamental points
GENEVA - Non-communicable diseases (NCDs), such as heart diseases, strokes, cancer, diabetes and chronic respiratory diseases, are responsible for 70% of all deaths.
There is irrefutable evidence that the use of tobacco, physical inactivity, poor diet and excessive alcohol consumption increase the risk of dying prematurely from non-communicable diseases.
Yet despite widespread awareness of the risks, global obesity is generally not controlled, while tobacco and alcohol consumption continue to rise.
It was in this context that non-communicable diseases alliance networks convened from December 9 to 11 at the second World Non-Communicable Diseases Alliance Forum in the United Arab Emirates.
In their search for solutions to regulate non-communicable diseases, they should draw inspiration from the HIV/AIDS fight movement.
People living with and affected by HIV continue to implement interventions, and their unique form of mobilization has been essential to the progress achieved.
As the battle is not yet over, HIV/AIDS activists know they can win this battle.
Similarly, a movement of mobilization against non-communicable diseases can reverse this epidemic.
Yet in 2015, Richard Horton, editor-in-chief of the journal The Lancet, described the non-communicable disease community as being in a state of « coma-like inertia » and asked: « But who will have the courage to administer it? »
We believe there are lessons to be learned from HIV/AIDS activists.
As global attention focuses on preventing non-communicable diseases, those seeking to control preventable diseases must draw inspiration from the ABC of HIV/AIDS advocacy organizations.
The first letter that the non-communicable diseases community must consider is « A », as activism.
Every person over the age of 40 surely remembers the images of HIV/AIDS activists participating in "die-ins" during scientific meetings around the world.
In the United States, HIV/AIDS activists took to the streets and even caused the closure of the Food and Drug Administration headquarters for a day in October 1988.
At the global level, activists have pressured governments and pharmaceutical companies to make medicines more affordable.
This activism continues and should serve as a model for action on non-communicable diseases.
Then, the non-communicable diseases community must adopt a more bold approach to budgets - the « B » of the HIV/AIDS movement strategy.
Civil organization and grassroots activism can mobilize the initial energies, but the organization and maintenance of a broad coalition require money.
The HIV/AIDS movement was clear on this from the beginning and exerted pressure to obtain resources to effectively support its awareness and empowerment activities.
« C » represents coalitions: the HIV/AIDS movements quickly realized that progress comes only with multiple supporters.
Activists have established links between people living with HIV and those with other concerns, such as women's rights, intellectual property rights, nutrition, and housing.
Coalitions and specialized campaigns work better when they bring together internal and external leaders from public authorities, in order to combine their perspectives and expertise.
The HIV/AIDS movement also understood that a global response to the epidemic is essential for the spread of its support.
Thus, "D," the determining factor of success, consisted of "drawing attention to the interconnectedness of the challenge."
For example, lobbying education leaders to keep girls in school longer has contributed to providing young people with the knowledge and power to make intelligent decisions about when and with whom to negotiate protected sexual relationships.
In the same way, links have been established between groups working on poverty, gender equality, and nutrition: all factors that played a driving role in the HIV/AIDS crisis.
Non-communicable diseases are not less isolated in their causality and also benefit from a multi-sectoral approach to prevention.
Engagement—“E”—was what helped the HIV/AIDS movement gain such great influence.
By drawing strategic inspiration from the disability rights movement, which championed the slogan "Nothing about us without us," HIV/AIDS advocates demanded the inclusion of representative bodies to address the disease.
For example, UNAIDS remains the only UN agency with seats on its governing body intended for representatives of civil society.
This standard is so deeply embedded in the HIV/AIDS movement that it would be almost unthinkable for an HIV/AIDS meeting to take place without community representation.
Prevention movements must also develop compelling narratives, and "F" — framing the issue — is essential for the HIV/AIDS community to gain political leaders' support.
In particular, access to HIV/AIDS treatment was presented as an issue of economic justice.
Framing the narrative in this way leads to a significant reduction in drug prices, to the extent that more than half of people living with HIV in low- and middle-income countries are on treatment.
A similarly important framing of the issue for HIV/AIDS, a highly relevant issue for the NCD movement, is that of responsibility.
The HIV/AIDS community has worked hard to place more emphasis on individual lifestyle choices, rather than attributing responsibility for healthcare provision and the elimination of legal discrimination to the state.
In the HIV/AIDS debate, gender – the "G" of our movement – was a significant issue.
HIV was initially seen as a "gay disease," and gender identity was embedded from the start in the DNA of the HIV/AIDS movement.
The gender dimensions of these diseases are no less important: one need only examine how alcohol and tobacco are marketed to understand this.
Gender, therefore, must become a focal point of NCD prevention efforts.
Finally, "H" — human rights — form the foundation of the HIV/AIDS response.
Campaigns have been launched against discrimination in workplaces, schools, and medical centers.
The strategic dispute ensured equality under the law.
The HIV/AIDS movement refused to hold major conferences in countries with repressive laws against people living with HIV.
The NCD movement could adopt the same tactic, for example, by refusing to hold meetings in countries that fail to restrict the advertising of unhealthy foods to children.
We could continue through the entire alphabet listing the lessons learned from the fight against HIV/AIDS, but it seems appropriate to close the list on "H," given that human rights provided the response to HIV/AIDS and should provide the response to non-communicable diseases.
Poverty, exclusion, as well as social and economic marginalization put people at greater risk of HIV.
The same applies to NCDs.
The first reaction to the HIV/AIDS epidemic was to ask: "Why don't these people make better choices?" The HIV/AIDS movement clearly stated that this question is not the right one.
Today, with 70% of the planet at risk of premature death due to preventable diseases, "these people" represent a large number of us.
The NCD and HIV/AIDS communities can learn from each other.
We are a stronger movement when we unite our strengths.
The opinions expressed here do not necessarily reflect those of UNAIDS.
